data.content:
## Migration: `BackgroundProcessor` â†’ .NET 8

### Pattern Classification

| Usage | Pattern | Replacement |
|-------|---------|-------------|
| `while (_running)` + `Thread.Abort()` | Cancellable work loop | `CancellationToken` |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | Control flow cleanup | `catch (OperationCanceledException)` |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | Continue after abort | `token.IsCancellationRequested` check |
| `GetNextItem()` blocking | Blocking call interruption | Pass token to unblock |

### Why This Breaks on .NET 8

`Thread.Abort()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` â€” there's no forced termination. The `catch (ThreadAbortException)` block will **never execute**, so `RollbackCurrentTransaction()` silently stops running. Your `Stop()` method will wait 2 seconds then crash.

### Migrated Code

```csharp
public class BackgroundProcessor : IDisposable
{
    private Thread? _workerThread;
    private CancellationTokenSource? _cts;

    public void Start()
    {
        _cts = new CancellationTokenSource();
        _workerThread = new Thread(() => ProcessLoop(_cts.Token));
        _workerThread.IsBackground = true;
        _workerThread.Start();
    }

    private void ProcessLoop(CancellationToken token)
    {
        while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            try
            {
                // Pass token so blocking calls can be interrupted
                var item = GetNextItem(token);
                ProcessItem(item, token);
            }
            catch (OperationCanceledException) when (token.IsCancellationRequested)
            {
                // Replaces the ThreadAbortException catch block.
                // Critical: this cleanup previously relied on Thread.Abort
                // injecting an exception â€” now it fires via cooperative check.
                RollbackCurrentTransaction();

                // No Thread.ResetAbort needed â€” we control whether the
                // loop continues via the while condition. The loop will
                // exit naturally because token.IsCancellationRequested is true.
            }
            finally
            {
                FlushBuffers();
            }
        }
    }

    public void Stop()
    {
        if (_cts is null) return;

        _cts.Cancel(); // signals cooperative cancellation

        // Join with timeout instead of Sleep + Abort
        if (_workerThread is not null && _workerThread.IsAlive)
        {
            if (!_workerThread.Join(TimeSpan.FromSeconds(2)))
            {
                // Thread didn't stop in time. In .NET 8 there is NO way
                // to force-kill it. Log a warning â€” the thread will exit
                // at its next cancellation checkpoint.
                Console.Error.WriteLine(
                    "Warning: worker thread did not stop within timeout.");
            }
        }
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        Stop();
        _cts?.Dispose();
    }
}
```

### Key Changes to `GetNextItem`

Your original `GetNextItem()` "may block" â€” this is the biggest pitfall. If it blocks indefinitely, cancellation **never fires** because cooperative cancellation only works at checkpoints. You must modify it to accept a token:

```csharp
// BEFORE: blocks indefinitely, only Thread.Abort could interrupt
private WorkItem GetNextItem() {
    return _queue.Take(); // BlockingCollection.Take()
}

// AFTER: unblocks when token is cancelled
private WorkItem GetNextItem(CancellationToken token) {
    return _queue.Take(token); // throws OperationCanceledException
}
```

If `GetNextItem` uses raw `Monitor.Wait`, `socket.Receive`, or similar:

```csharp
// Replace Thread.Sleep with cancellation-aware wait
Thread.Sleep(5000);                    // âťŚ won't respond to cancellation
token.WaitHandle.WaitOne(5000);        // âś… returns early on cancel

// Replace WaitHandle.WaitOne with cancellation-aware version
event.WaitOne();                                          // âťŚ
WaitHandle.WaitAny(new[] { event, token.WaitHandle });    // âś…
```

### Critical Pitfalls

| Pitfall | Details |
|---------|---------|
| **`RollbackCurrentTransaction` stops running** | On .NET Framework, `Thread.Abort` injected `ThreadAbortException` *anywhere* in `ProcessItem`. On .NET 8, `OperationCanceledException` only fires from code that checks the token. If `ProcessItem` doesn't check the token, the catch block won't fire mid-work â€” add `token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested()` at checkpoints inside `ProcessItem`. |
| **Blocking calls ignore the token** | `Thread.Sleep`, `socket.Receive`, `Console.ReadLine` â€” none of these check `CancellationToken`. Replace with async or `WaitHandle`-based alternatives (shown above). |
| **`CancellationTokenSource` must be disposed** | It allocates timers/callbacks internally. The `IDisposable` pattern above handles this. |
| **`Thread.Join` replaces `Sleep` + `Abort`** | The original `Sleep(2000)` then `Abort` was a two-phase shutdown. Use `Thread.Join(timeout)` for a clean wait, but understand that if the thread doesn't cooperate, you **cannot** force it to stop in .NET 8. |
| **`ResetAbort` has no equivalent** | There's nothing to reset. If you want the loop to continue processing after a cancellation (as `ResetAbort` allowed), use a *per-item* `CancellationTokenSource` linked to a parent token, and create a new one for each iteration. |

### If You Need Per-Item Cancellation (ResetAbort Equivalent)

```csharp
private void ProcessLoop(CancellationToken shutdownToken)
{
    while (!shutdownToken.IsCancellationRequested)
    {
        // New token per work item â€” can cancel one item without
        // stopping the whole loop (mimics ResetAbort behavior)
        using var itemCts = CancellationTokenSource
            .CreateLinkedTokenSource(shutdownToken);
        try
        {
            var item = GetNextItem(shutdownToken);
            ProcessItem(item, itemCts.Token);
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException)
            when (!shutdownToken.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            // Item-level cancellation â€” rollback and continue
            RollbackCurrentTransaction();
            continue;
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException)
            when (shutdownToken.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            RollbackCurrentTransaction();
            break; // full shutdown
        }
        finally
        {
            FlushBuffers();
        }
    }
}
```

The fundamental shift: **you** control when and where cancellation is checked â€” the runtime no longer injects exceptions at arbitrary points.
